+---
+title: Execution patterns
+description: How queue-level execution patterns (static-dag, pipeline, map-reduce) layer above the tick engine — pattern config, the gate/respawn circle-back, extendRun + run.extended audit entries, and the forward-arc-never-rewind invariant.
+---
+
+The core tick engine described in
+[How an offload run executes](/pangolin/explanation/how-offload-runs/) is intentionally
+fixed: it processes a DAG you gave it at submit time and nothing more. **Execution
+patterns** are the layer above that engine that lets a run grow safely *while it runs*
+— a map step fans out to N workers whose count was unknown at submit time, or a gate
+step fails validation and respawns a fix pass before continuing downstream. This page
+explains how patterns work, how you configure them per queue, and what invariants keep
+the graph acyclic and auditable no matter what a pattern emits.
+
+## What an execution pattern is
+
+An execution pattern is a **pure, stateless strategy object** bound to a queue. After
+each engine tick completes its four phases (ready → reconcile → fire → cascade), the
+orchestrator runs a **pattern phase**: for every unsealed run on a pattern-bound queue
+it calls `collectSpawns`, which iterates each terminal item in the run and calls
+`pattern.onTaskDone(item, { runItems })` once per item, collecting non-null
+**spawn directives** — descriptions of new WorkItems to add to the run.
+
+Three built-in patterns cover the common shapes of dynamic work:
+
+- **`static-dag`** — `onTaskDone` returns null for every item. The graph submitted is
+  the graph that runs. Use this when you know every step at submission time.
+- **`pipeline`** — each stage gate can respawn a repair pass. When a gate item
+  terminates `failed` (or completes but is marked red by the verifier), the pattern
+  emits a fix item, a gate copy, and copies of any downstream items that were cascaded
+  to `skipped` — wiring the repair forward so execution continues. The failed branch
+  becomes sealed history; the repair branch becomes the live path.
+- **`map-reduce`** — a splitter item runs first and writes the set of shards to its
+  output refs; on the splitter's completion `onTaskDone` emits one map worker per
+  shard. The reduce item is spawned only when every map worker has reached `done`
+  status. Neither the map workers nor the reduce item exist at submit time; they are
+  created by the pattern as the run progresses.
+
+Patterns are deliberately kept pure and stateless. They re-derive the same spawn
+directives every time they scan the same terminal items — this is what makes them
+crash-safe (see [Replay safety](#replay-safety-by-construction) below).
+
+## Queue-level pattern config
+
+Patterns are configured in `pangolin.config` at the queue level, not at the run level.
+Every run submitted to that queue inherits the queue's pattern:
+
+```jsonc
+// pangolin.config.ts (excerpt)
+{
+  "orchestrator": {
+    "queues": [
+      {
+        "name": "pipeline-q",
+        "concurrency": 2,
+        "pattern": {
+          "type": "pipeline"
+        }
+      },
+      {
+        "name": "fanout-q",
+        "concurrency": 8,
+        "pattern": {
+          "type": "map-reduce"
+        }
+      }
+    ]
+  }
+}
+```
+
+A queue with no `pattern` key has no pattern bound to it: the pattern phase
+short-circuits immediately, no `extendRun` calls are made, and the run seals the tick
+everything goes terminal. The `static-dag` pattern object exists but is not installed
+as an automatic fallback — an unbound queue and a `static-dag`-bound queue produce
+identical runtime behaviour.
+
+For `map-reduce`, the per-shard and reducer behaviour is not carried in the queue-level
+config: it is embedded in each splitter item's `inputs.mapReduce` field (a
+`MapReduceConfig` with `map` and `reduce` templates). This means different splitters in
+different runs can use different executors or inputs, all on the same queue.
+
+Pattern-specific config (the `inputs.mapReduce` object on a splitter item, the
+`inputs.gate` object on a gate item) is validated inside `pat.plan(run)`, which runs
+during `submitRun` — before any item is written to the store. A malformed config
+therefore surfaces as a submission error, not a runtime one, leaving the store clean.
+
+## The gate/respawn circle-back
+
+The most important pattern behaviour — and the one most likely to surprise — is the
+**gate/respawn circle-back** in the `pipeline` pattern.
+
+A *gate* item is a validation step that sits between two stages of a pipeline. Its
+`inputs.gate` carries a `GateConfig`: `onRed: 'spawn-fix'`, a `subject` (the id of the
+upstream item whose product the gate validated), and a `fixTemplate` (executor and
+inputs for the repair agent). If the gate succeeds, dependents proceed normally. If it
+fails (or completes but is marked red by the verifier), the pipeline does not stop: the
+pattern emits a *fix item* whose `depends_on` points at the subject — the upstream item
+that produced the work being repaired — plus a *gate copy* whose `depends_on` points at
+the fix. Every item that was cascaded to `skipped` as a result of the gate's failure
+gets a fresh copy with its dependency edges remapped through the same substitution map,
+so execution continues through the repaired path.
+
+Crucially, this is **not** a cycle in the graph. The failed gate item stays in the
+graph as a terminal `failed` node. Existing items' `depends_on` edges are **never
+mutated**; instead, copies of the skipped descendants are spawned with remapped edges.
+The graph grows forward; the failed subtree is permanently sealed as history.
+
+```
+submit-time graph:
+
+  fetch → lint-gate → deploy
+
+after lint-gate fails, pattern emits three new items:
+
+  fetch → lint-gate(failed)
+            ↓
+  lint-gate-fix-1  (depends on fetch, the gate's subject)
+            ↓
+  lint-gate~2      (gate copy, depends on fix)
+            ↓
+  deploy~2         (copy of the skipped deploy, depends on lint-gate~2)
+```
+
+From the engine's perspective there is nothing special here: `lint-gate-fix-1`,
+`lint-gate~2`, and `deploy~2` are ordinary WorkItems added via `extendRun`, with
+ordinary `depends_on` edges. The pattern is only responsible for computing *what* to
+add; the engine handles scheduling, locking, and retry exactly as for any other item.
+
+`maxFixAttempts` (default `1`) on the `GateConfig` caps how many times this
+circle-back may fire per original gate. When the cap is reached and the latest gate
+copy still fails, the pattern emits nothing — the gate is terminally failed, its
+transitive dependents cascade to `skipped`, and the run settles.
+
+## extendRun and run.extended audit entries
+
+Spawn directives are applied through a single audited seam: **`extendRun`**.
+
+`extendRun` does exactly what `submitRun` does on initial submission, for the
+incremental case:
+
+1. Validates the new items against the *merged* graph (existing items plus the
+   additions) using the same `validateRun` function used at submit time — no cycles,
+   no dangling `depends_on` references, no duplicate ids.
+2. Inserts the new items into the run-state store in `pending` status.
+3. Writes a **`run.extended`** audit entry that names the actor (`pattern:<queueName>`),
+   the cause item (the terminal item that triggered the spawn), and the timestamp.
+
+Because `extendRun` runs inside the same tick as the pattern phase, and the seal check
+runs *after* the pattern phase, a run that just grew structurally cannot seal that
+tick — the new `pending` items prevent it. This is the correct ordering: seal-then-check
+would produce an audit gap between when items exist and when they appear in the log.
+
+Provenance closure over dynamically grown graphs requires no additional verifier logic.
+Spawned items append to the same run and consume upstream products via the same `needs`
+machinery; `checkHandoffClosure` therefore already covers them with no change to the
+verifier code. The `run.extended` entry is what makes the extension visible in the
+audit bundle, but the closure invariant is upheld by construction rather than by
+log-replay reconstruction.
+
+## Replay safety by construction
+
+Patterns keep no mutable state between calls. Every call to `onTaskDone` receives a
+single terminal item plus the full `runItems` context, and re-derives its spawn
+directive from scratch. Spawn item ids are **deterministic** — computed from the cause
+item id and the attempt number, not from a counter or timestamp — so running `onTaskDone`
+twice on the same input produces the same ids.
+
+`extendRun` enforces idempotency at the store level: any id already present in the run
+is silently skipped. Together these two properties mean that a crash between the pattern
+phase and the seal check, followed by a restart and re-scan, re-derives exactly the
+same directives and `extendRun` absorbs them as a no-op. No dedup logic is needed
+beyond what the store already provides for initial submission.
+
+## The forward-arc-never-rewind invariant
+
+All spawn directives must satisfy one hard invariant: **no spawned item may be the
+`depends_on` target of any item that already exists in the graph.**
+
+In plain terms: `extendRun` never modifies an existing item's `depends_on` edges.
+Existing items cannot be made to depend on new items. New items may freely depend on
+old items *or* on other new items in the same batch — for instance, `respawnLineage`
+emits a gate copy that depends on the freshly spawned fix item, both arriving in the
+same `extendRun` call. The graph grows by **appending** (new leaves, or new internal
+nodes with backward-pointing or intra-batch edges), never by inserting edges into
+existing items.
+
+`extendRun`'s `validateRun` call enforces this structurally: after merging the new
+items into the existing graph it runs a topological sort and rejects any cycle. Because
+existing items' `depends_on` edges cannot be modified after submission, no new item can
+create a cycle through an existing item. The only edges that can reference new items are
+edges *from* new or other newly-added items in the same batch.
+
+This invariant has three practical consequences:
+
+- **Settled history stays settled.** A terminal item is terminal forever. A pattern
+  cannot "re-open" a completed step by inserting a dependency on it from an earlier
+  point in the graph. The audit log's past is immutable.
+- **The engine needs no special handling for dynamic runs.** The tick loop processes
+  the graph it sees at each tick. New items are pending when they arrive; they ready
+  when their `depends_on` complete; they fire, reconcile, and terminate exactly like
+  submit-time items. No tick-loop code was modified to support patterns.
+- **`pangolin verify` terminates.** Because the graph is always acyclic, the topological
+  walk the verifier uses to check provenance closure always terminates and always
+  produces a unique ordering. A dynamic run is not a special case for verification;
+  it is just a larger acyclic graph.
+
